{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783127780,"nonce":"x7FqWbidD8n3bu4cb1/E6uApmUQ=","title":"SQLite: introspect table CHECK constraints and column collations","message":"The squealy-sqlite renderer currently REJECTS table CHECK constraints (write_check) and column collations (write_column), because SQLite exposes neither to introspection — there is no PRAGMA for them; they live only in the CREATE TABLE text. A published CHECK/collation would therefore diff as a never-settling change on every plan, so they are rejected rather than silently dropped.\n\nTo support them, introspection needs to parse the stored CREATE TABLE SQL (sqlite_master.sql) to recover:\n- table-level CHECK constraint expressions (and their derived/canonical names), and\n- per-column COLLATE clauses.\n\nOnce introspectable, drop the rejections in write_check/write_column and add them to the renderer + rebuild path, with churn-free round-trip tests. This is the same CREATE TABLE-text parsing that SQLite table comments would need (also unsupported/rejected). Split off from the SQLite backend bug a92e39f (PR 4b).","files":null}]}